description.text:
Well, here it is. Definitive proof that you can create affordable, tabletop quality, 28mm scale miniatures on a 3D printer. Konstantin Krieger printed this on his Incube3D SLA printer for me, and I thought I should go ahead and post the model after I painted it. This was every bit as easy to paint as a Games Workshop or Reaper model. As an aside, I forget that I love working with the "Cthulhu palette."

A couple of quick notes: We're currently running a Kickstarter campaign for the 15mm scale sci-fi buildings I've been posting the last few weeks, so if you're into 15mm scale gaming and you don't have a printer of your own, come drop us a pledge and get some swag! Also, to celebrate our new campaign, we've made the PDF version of our tabletop RPG, Wayfarer: Things Beyond Wonder FREE to download for the remainder of our Kickstarter campaign (so, through May 15th), so if you like tabletop roleplaying and want to check it out, hit the link and give it a download. You don't have to be a backer to get it, so tell your friends!

We've set up a Patreon page for anyone who's interested in helping to fund us so we can keep making free and open sourced games like Pocket-Tactics, Wayfarer Tactics. and others, not to mention the growing catalog of gaming miniatures that you can use for whatever you want! (Psst... we take requests and commissions...)

Enjoy!

This is a fume scrubber for a 3d printer enclosure designed to use an 80mm computer fan and activated charcoal from any pet store. Plus a few nuts and bolts and some prefilter material, although it works fine without probably best to keep dust out of the charcoal itself, also you could make the box part thinner if you were not using prefilter material as you do not need 19mm of charcoal. So far I can't detect the smell of PLA when printing with this scrubber.

After using this a few months, It eliminates the smell of PLA for me, and I finally got around to trying ABS, it cuts the smell down allot, but its still there, and since ABS is generally seen as not healthy to breathe, I recommend some of the other designs on here that use Gas mask canisters or pumping the fumes outside.

Your cats never have to settle for substandard food portions again! Now, instead of getting 2/5 or 5/16 of a can of food, they can get precisely 1/3 of a can! Even better, they can get multiples of 1/3 dished out precisely as well. 1/3, 2/3, yes, even 3/3 of a can of food can now be precisely dished out! Download yours today!

There is a 3 oz and 5.5 oz version (common US sizes), plus an OpenSCAD customizable version that will work with the customizer if you have a different size can or different portion requirements. I've only printed and used the 5.5 oz version 3 portion size. The 3 oz version is based on some reconnaissance at the pet store, so may be a mm off. Let me know so I can fix it, since I wasn't willing to pay $1 for a can of cat food to verify myself. And my cats only like 1 and 1/3 cans of food per meal, so I never bothered to try the cat food quarterer or cat food sixther.

Notes on food safety:
3D prints are hard to make truly food safe, so use some caution here to keep your kitties safe and healthy.

Use a food safe plastic.
Constantly wonder if the nozzle, hot end, filament guides, spool, and filament maker, are all also food safe.
Coat the whole thing with a food safe coating to fill in the gaps left by your printer and keep that questionable plastic away from the food.
Just make a mold and recast in a food safe resin.

title: Qidi Tech Build Platform Jog Z-Axis Brace / Rest / Scrape Platform Tool

description.text:
This platform is used when jogging the Z-Axis down to rest on something, in this case a specific lightweight platform. It's useful for alleviating stress on the Z-Axis rods when servicing or scraping the print bed. This allows you to put A LOT more force down so be mindful of the stresses introduced to the machine parts as to not damage or bend anything. I was using a block of wood prior but figured I'd create something lighter that serves this specific purpose.

This will work for the Flashforge Creator Pro also and a 148mm version has been added for upgraded Qidi machines.

Notes:

Printed in ABS with 3 shell layers, 7 top and bottom layers. My infill for these parts was 30% and layer height 0.2mm, feel free to change them to your desired amounts. Mine seems to have printed with minor supports to keep the angles perfect as I had them turned on by default but I think you may be able to get away without them.

I lower the print-bed slowly on the Z-Axis while watching from the side until I see the rails touch the bottom of the platform slots slightly and then it should be braced. You want the print-bed to be very close to level when braced and not to over-stress the Z-Axis support rods.

When lowering the Z-Axis onto the slots, please be mindful of your wingnuts and print-bed heater wiring. I haven't tried leaving it in there while printing but I assume it would work as when the print-bed goes to its lowest Z-Axis home point, there is still space between the bottom of the print-bed rails and the slots.

description.text:
Hi there!

I've designed the aligner, after having problems with filament's feeding into the extruder.

At first I thought I was having clogs... then I thought it could be an issue with the temperature control (I got the covers "just in case")... swapping spools... etc.
After trying everything, including replacing the entire hot-end, nothing seemed to work.
So I went piece by piece, examining what could be causing this. And I found out that the hole that holds the filament tube, is in a "bottleneck" shape and too tight for the tube. So I thought this could be the source of the problem... and it was!! It causes too much friction to the filament, so eventually it'll be too much drag for the extruder gear to pull.

After I've installed the aligner, the filament goes free into the extruder, with no resistance, and it works great. As you can see in the photos, now there's a gap between the aligner and the extruder hole.

I hope you find it useful!

Cheers,

description.text:
BULLETZ are really cool Bullet shaped containers with a screw cap. They are easy to print and look best with the bullet (cap) printed in a different colour from the cartridge (container).

BULLETZ are useful as a container for small things and the near seamless joint (when print well and screwed together) make them an ideal hiding place for things... because they look like an ornament / display model. People won't realize there's something hidden inside!

The bullet (cap) and cartridge (container) are printed separately. The cartridge is 11.5cm tall making it readily printable on even smaller machines like a MakerBot Mini. When the bullet and cartridge are screwed together the finished product is approx. 16cm tall

The 'flat cap' stl file has been added for people wanting a container that just looks like the bullet casing without the pointed bullet as well. This provides a threaded cap for the casing that screws on just the same as the bullet cap.

As long as you have a well set up machine and use a good slicing app you should have no problem printing off BULLETZ. However, please refer to the print settings and instructions as well as view all the images provide.

The .stl's have been provided separately so you can print them together all in one colour or separately to make your BULLETZ more colourful. They print great in PLA and PET-G. No Support required but Raft is recommended due to the minimal base surface area under the bullet (cap) in particular.

Note: If you like this check out the rest of my fun and practical designs... and please post images of your BULLETZ for others to see.

title: Valve stabiliser for carbon road bike wheels

description.text: If you have carbon wheels and use long presta valves you will be familiar with the problem of valve rattle at higher speeds. No drama - just annoying. This is an example of how it is simply fixed with a small stabiliser. This is precisely tailored for Bontrager Aeolus 5's - but I suspect that the fine details of curvature don't really matter a whole lot; for most carbon wheels it will probably work perfectly well... If the fit is not snug enough for you - at least now you have the idea and can go and design your own!

The STL includes a separate flange which just ensures the air moving over the HPB does not lift the item. You can make lots of copies of this STL on your build plate to produce a batch. You will probably get better quality the more you print, since it will give more time for  each layer on a given stabiliser to cool. With small parts the layer print time can be so quick that the print remains plastic and deforms during the printing process. With more time to cool, each item will be dimensionally more accurate.  
This is an incredibly simple bike tweak that works perfectly - without adding more than a gram or two to the bike. (Daft issue I know - but some people worry about these things ;-) )

description.text:
This is a derivative of Skimbal's CD-Rom Motor Pump. I added a space for my Hose Adapter which makes it possible to use the pump with almost any hose.

My version is as well as Skimbal's designed for a CD-Rom Motor which you can get out of CD and DVD-drives. They are usually 6V DC motors, however I used 7.2V in the Video (not recommended for long running times). I also played a bit around with blender, so I added a rendered image and the Blender-file.

Customization

Use the OpenSCAD or the Customizer to make the adapter fitting to your needs (PumpHoseApapter.scad or http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1494628).
You should not take a too big hose (Ø over 6mm) or you won't get a nice flow of your fluid at least not as high a with let's say a diameter of 4 or 3mm.

1) Print out your customized hose adapter, the casing, the base and of course the impreller. I used PLA, but ABS and PET will last longer especially when exposed to sunlight, water or other fluids.

2) Drill out the center of the impeller so it fits on the motor's shaft

3) Use a knife to cut the support tower out of the center of the casing

4) Press the motor firmly into the top of the casing

5) Press the impeller down onto the motor shaft, but not all the way. Leave a little space between the top of the impeller and the base of the housing.

6) Power the motor and use sandpaper against the spinning impeller to smooth out any high spots

7) Place the adapter in it's space (you might have to make it fitting with sandpaper or a file, be careful to not remove to much)

8) Press the base on

9) Attach your hose (you might have to fix it with a

DONE!

Now you can pump fluids around. BUT be careful with hydrazin, nitroglycerin and other dangerous fluids or you might destroy a bit more then your pump.

description.text:
Description;

This model is my take on a dremel based drill press mount. I've seen quite a few but I wanted to make one in a day with parts I had on hand, so I just designed, printed and made my own. This version does not use linear bearings, just 10mm smooth rods direct contact with the main carriage, which has four tightening screws.

The brackets for mounting the dremel is changeable and modular, so the press can be changed to fit different equipment

(haven't made any other brackets than ones for my own dremel, fits 50mm+/-3 tools, do request parts though)

Required parts;

4 - 175mm long, 10mm smooth rods
1 - 65...110mm long, M6 threaded rod
1 - 125mm long, M6 threaded rod

18 - M4 nuts
7 - M6 nuts
2 - M3 nuts (or some kind of thumb screw, still M3)

18 - 15mm long, M4 bolts (preferably umbraco)
2 - 25...40mm long, M3 bolts

(Optional;)
8 - Mounting screws of choice, MAX head dia; 8mm, prefered coned wood screws
2 - Springs of choice. MIN 11mm inner dia, preferably 30...40mm long and reasonably strong

Other;

Additionally i want to give credit to mitchnajmitch for the gear and gear strip, I have remodeled them more or less completely but those two parts were based on his design.

comments.text: I used an old coffee jug thin glass pour a little acetone in the bottom just cover the bottom and put on the heat bed you will see the vapour level rise up the sides of the glass suspend the piece bellow this level and you will see the plastic gloss do not leave too long else will weaken the part remove and allow to dry before touching else you will spoil the finish.

comments.text: Wet a paper towel with it, put it to the side in a container (one that won't melt with acetone!), put the print in not touching the acetone-wetted paper towel, close up the container for a few seconds (like, 20-30s).  Do that for a few intervals until it's smoothed out how you like and not so much that it's melting more than the outer layer(s) or you might actually weaken your print. 1 A Li-Ion Charger Case

This case is designed for a TP4056 1A LiPo/Liion charger that can charge 18650's batteries. To build this you will need additional parts.

parts list

  • TP4056
  • 18650 battery holder

assembly

After printing solder the wires of the positive and negative terminals of the battery holder to the according pads on the charger. Then insert the charger upside down into the printed case. Keep in mind that the wire of the positive terminal needs to feed through under the charger up to the front of the case. After that place the battery holder onto it and screw it in place. It helps to glue down some of the wires beforehand to make the assembly easier. You can choose to either use an M3 nut and screw or just any other screw that fits. I also trimmed off some parts of the battery holder, because the battery was held in too hard and when removing the battery the case could break.

title: optical endstop mount and adjustable target

description.text:
First of all this is my first posted 'thing'. When I made it I wasn't thinking of posting it, so sorry there aren't any pics of the parts not assembled or of the assembly process.

I used a brass 3mm threaded insert in the target piece pushed in with a soldering iron, but you could probably just as well thread the screw directly into the plastic. The screw itself passes through the top, with a washer under the head, another washer, then a fiber lock nut. Tighten the nut until there is no slop in the screw, but still easy enough to turn. The holes in the lower part are to be a press fit for the brass rods, and the holes in the upper part are a slide fit. I had to clean the holes up slightly with a rat tale file for the correct fit. I used 3mm brass rod, but you could use whatever fits. The top unit is then bonded to the X carriage part using plastic solvent. The stuff used for making plastic models and can be found at hobby shops (not the stuff in the tube, this stuff us water thin and is in a jar.

The base that actually holds the optical end stop, I drew long to cut short to the desired length. There are no holes in it for screws. For now I just stuck the end stop on it with double sided sticky pad. I may change it later, but it works fine.

Hope this helps someone,

I engineer submarines for a living, so I decided to spice up my cubicle a bit with this name tag. It has pin tabs up top for use with thumb tacks, which can be easily be snipped off with some flush cutters. The other option for mounting is a couple of holes into which you can glue small neodymium magnets from Harbor Freight (http://www.harborfreight.com/10-piece-rare-earth-magnets-67488.html). I achieved my best results by printing with zero bottom layers to allow flex in the infill to absorb any thermal stresses and avoid bed separation. Using 10-15% rectangular infill, 2 perimeters, and 3 top layers with a 0.4mm nozzle gives a very nice surface finish.

title: Wanhao Duplicator i3 Adjustable Z-Axis Limit Switch Mount

description.text:
Yet another adjustable z-axis limit switch mount. I wanted a mount that had coarse and fine adjustments, required no printer modification, used the existing stock switch and stock screws, was completely printable, and had no additional parts required.

All of these goals have been met. However, the mount is more robust if a rubber band, like that from a news paper, or two small springs, like those from a retractable ink pen, are incorporated to help dampen the small motion due to moving part interface tolerances.

The design uses an interchangeable clipping switch mount that press fits onto the adjustment rods. Two common switch dimensions have been implemented. Others, including optical limit switches, would be easy to add.

For each of the two switch sizes, there is a design version for use with springs and another for a rubber band. The mswich_13a_XXX versions are for use with the stock switch in the Wanhao Duplicator i3. So if you are not replacing your limit switch, start here and choose between:

1) mswitch_13a-build_plate_s.stl - stock switch spring version
2) mswitch_13a-build_plate_b.stl - stock switch rubber band version

There are build plates for the resulting four combinations. If you need to print an individual component, the zip archive contains all of the rendered STL model combinations.

As configured, the spring version of the mount enables approximately 20mm or coarse (-5mm to +15mm), and 10mm of fine (+/-5mm) adjustments.

This design makes use of the thread Screw Library.

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

Print for accuracy and strength. I have had the better results when printing at lower print speeds.

• Hone the two guide rod holes and center threaded rod hole with with drill bits. No need a to use a powered drill; just turn the bits inside the hole to clear out any burs and irregularities. I have used an 11/64" bit for threaded rod hole and 5/32" for guide rod holes. Don't over do it. The rods should fit snugly but slide without requiring lots of axial force.

  • Work the thumb wheel down the threads a few time to clean them up.

  • Insert each end of the rods, one at a time, into the switch mount separately and gently rotate to smooth the inner hole and outer posts surfaces.

  • File/sand the thumb wheel slot and wheel surface, as needed, to obtain smooth insertion and rotation of the wheel in the slot.

  • Assemble the pieces together. Make sure the switch mount is fully seated. Place switch mount upside down on a firm table and press the rods down into the mount.

  • If the lead or rod breaks, reprint it with higher infill. I have printed at 20% will no problems. The center threader rod carries the most force.
Rubber Band Version Assembly

When feeding the rubber band, an open paper clip and tweezers helps to navigate the small holes.

Assembly Front Assembly Back

Start with the knot recess at the front of the upper switch mount:

  • Feed the rubber band from the back and tie a knot at the front. Pull on the rubber band to countersink the knot at the front.
  • Feed the other end back through the bracket arm from the rear to the front.
  • Feed across the arm to the other side and then into the adjacent feed hole from front to back.
  • Finally feed from the back of the switch to the front and tie at the countersinking hole.

The YCOPTER is designed for the standard RCExplore tricopter motors (DT750) and servo (BMS-385DMAX), other components may or may not fit.
Additional parts and instructions:
  • 10mmX10mm bass wood or carbon fiber booms. 2X 275mm for the front arms, and 245mm for the tail.
  • 2X 3mm, 25mm bolt + 4X washers + 2X lock-nuts for the arm pivots. The pivot hole for each arm is located 5mm for the end, on center. (6-32 X 1" bolt/washer/nut set will also work with some drilling)
  • One 5mm X 50mm long bolt + 2X washers for the tail motor mount. (10-24 X 1" bolt/washer will also work) The tail boom needs to be drilled and tapped for the bolt thread. The printed tail motor mount through hole needs to be reamed out for a perfect fit. Lubricate the hole with Teflon or graphite powder.
  • Some 50lb Spectra fishing line or equivalent as the servo control cables. String the line as shown in the photo. Each side is a separate cable. Wrap some rubber band between the two cables to take up the slight slack.
  • 2X #4, 3/8" wood screws for mounting the servo.
  • 4X 3/4"id O-rings. Two O-rings on each arm keep it in place during flight. Slip them off to fold the arms during transport.
  • After the YCOPTER is assembled and aligned, improve rigidity by adding a bit of epoxy adhesive to the joins between the booms and printed parts; motor mounts, servo mount, legs and tail boom to body. Also put some on the cable knots to prevent them from untying.

description.text:
I designed this shift knob to approximate the dimensions of the stock R56 MINI Cooper shift knob measured with digital calipers, then used the imported Superman logo to place a raised logo on one shift knob, and an embossed logo on the other.

***PLEASE NOTE: the first file, with both designs (raised and embossed) is a generic treatment. The 2nd file is designed specifically for the R56 MINI Cooper shifter, with an adapter designed by TheAndrewBrown integrated into the design. (Link in Remix notes)

Once printed, I decided that the ebmossing should have gone another .2-.3mm deeper. I may go back and change that if the shallow indents make painting more difficult.

UPDATE 16 October, 2016: Redesigned the shift knob as a 2-pice design. The shifter has the Superman logo deeply indented, and then you can print the physical logo separately & it should insert into the indent in the knob. Idea being to print the knob in blue & the logo in red, so no need to paint. 2 new files added. ***I have printed & assembled this successfully, but beware- it takes violent, brute force to seat the logo in the knob. Not kidding.
